title: A Randomised, Double-Blind, Placebo Controlled, Single and Multiple Ascending Dose Study to Assess the Safety, Tolerability, Pharmacokinetics and Pharmacodynamics of MEDI1814 in Subjects With Mild to Moderate Alzheimer's Disease.
description_brief: The purpose of this study is to assess the safety, drug levels and effects on the body of 1 or 3 injections of MEDI1814, in people with mild to moderate Alzhiemer's Disease or healthy elderly people.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: Due to population (mild to moderate Alzheimer's disease) and duration (6 or 9 months) per cohort, rescreening was permitted. SAD had 128 screeings in105 subjects (23 rescreens); MAD had 133 screenings in 88 subjects, (22 rescreens from SAD and 23 rescreens from MAD). Note: 11 of 32 randomized MAD subjects had previously completed a SAD cohort.
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: 261 screening visits in 193 individuals were required to randomize 45 subjects into 6 Single Ascending Dose (SAD) cohorts and 32 subjects into 4 Multiple Ascending Dose (MAD) cohorts.

drug: MEDI1814 — a fully human monoclonal antibody selective for amyloid‑beta 42 (Aβ42), developed to lower free Aβ42 in CSF and plasma.
placebo: Placebo (IV and SC, used in the randomized double‑blind placebo‑controlled SAD/MAD study).
explanation_target: Reason: The investigational agent MEDI1814 is described in the literature as a fully human high‑affinity monoclonal antibody selective for Aβ42 (the pathogenic, self‑aggregating species of amyloid‑β), and clinical PD data show dose‑dependent suppression of free CSF Aβ42 — i.e., it targets Alzheimer’s pathology rather than functioning as a symptomatic cognitive enhancer or a neuropsychiatric treatment. citeturn0search0turn0search1

Act (extracted key details): MEDI1814 — monoclonal antibody selective for Aβ42; trial was randomized, double‑blind, placebo‑controlled single‑ and multiple‑ascending dose (SAD/MAD) in mild‑to‑moderate AD and healthy elderly, given IV or SC; primary assessments included safety, tolerability, pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics (CSF/plasma Aβ measures). citeturn0search2turn0search3turn0search1

Reflect: Classifying this as a 'disease‑targeted biologic' matches the definitions provided (biologic targeting AD pathology). No substantial ambiguity in mechanism or intended effect was found in the trial description and publications. citeturn0search0turn0search1

explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational agent MEDI1814 is a fully human monoclonal antibody selective for Aβ42 (binds the C‑terminus of Aβ42) and was developed to lower pathogenic Aβ42 (free CSF and plasma) — i.e., it directly targets amyloid‑β pathology rather than symptomatic pathways. citeturn0search0turn0search1turn0search2

Act: Extracted details from the trial description and publications — MEDI1814: monoclonal IgG1λ directed to the C‑terminus of Aβx‑42 with Fc modifications to reduce effector function; tested in randomized, double‑blind, placebo‑controlled single‑ and multiple‑ascending dose SAD/MAD studies in mild‑to‑moderate AD (IV and SC). Pharmacodynamics showed dose‑dependent suppression of free CSF Aβ42, increases in total (bound+free) Aβ42, with no change in Aβ40 and no ARIA reported in the study. These details indicate the drug’s mechanism is anti‑amyloid (Aβ42) target engagement. citeturn0search1turn0search0turn0search3
